# Compiling on Darwin

eb656

in Markdown formatting:
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

MOPS is pretty flexible (to my knowledge) on GCC and Boost Versions, so long that
Boost and MOPS are compiled with the same GCC version. 

Using the native CMAKE 3.9.4, it would find boost but fail to link it. HPC helped
find the solutions listed below. This is not exactly clear from the make error. 

>Linking CXX executable bin/PAHkmc-app
>lib/libchemkinReader.a(chemkinReader.cpp.o): In function `ZN5boost12regex_searchIN9gnu_cxx17normal_iteratorIPKcNSt7cxx1112basic_stringIcSt11char_traitsIcESaIcEEEEESaINS_9sub_matchISB_EEEcNS_12regex_traitsIcNS_16cpp_regex_traitsIcEEEEEEbT_SJ_RNS_13match_resultsISJ_T0_EERKNS_11basic_regexIT1_T2_EENS_15regex_constants12_match_flagsESJ.constprop.294':chemkinReader.cpp.text+0xa10): undefined reference to `boost::re_detail_106501::perl_matcher<_gnu_cxx::normal_iterator<char const*, std::cxx11::basic_string<char, std::char_traits<char>, std::allocator<char> > >, std::allocator<boost::sub_match<gnu_cxx::normal_iterator<char const*, std::cxx11::basic_string<char, std::char_traits<char>, std::allocator<char> > > > >, boost::regex_traits<char, boost::cpp_regex_traits<char> > >::construct_init(boost::basic_regex<char, boost::regex_traits<char, boost::cpp_regex_traits<char> > > const&, boost::regex_constants::_match_flags)'



## Installing MOPS on DARWIN

Steps:

+ load gcc module you want to use
+ load boost module that corresponds with that gcc compiler
+ export CC and CXX env vars
+ Address Linking boost problems:
  + Explicitly add paths to LD_LIBRARY_PATH, INCLUDE, and LIBRARY_PATH

or
 
  + Force CMAKE to use absolute paths.  


### Example Method 1

1. git clone as listed above. 
2. make release directory

New Commands:

3. module load gcc/5.2.0
4. module load boost/1.62-python2.7.10-gcc5.2.0
5. module display gcc 5.2.0 #Find executable path
6. module display boost/1.62-python2.7.10-gcc5.2.0 #Find boost Lib path 
7. export CC=/usr/local/Cluster-Apps/gcc/5.2.0/bin/gcc
8. export CXX=/usr/local/Cluster-Apps/gcc/5.2.0/bin/g++
9. export LD_LIBRARY_PATH=/usr/local/Cluster-Apps/boost/1.62/python2.7.10-gcc5.2.0/stage/lib:$LD_LIBRARY_PATH
10. export INCLUDE=/usr/local/Cluster-Apps/boost/1.62/python2.7.10-gcc5.2.0:$INCLUDE
11. export LIBRARY_PATH=/usr/local/Cluster-Apps/boost/1.62/python2.7.10-gcc5.2.0/stage/lib:$LIBRARY_PATH

Same as before: 

12. cmake -D CMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release ..
13. make -j 4   #for 4 threads of compilation (more if you can!)
14. ctest -j 4  #for 4 threads of testing

### Example Method 2 Untested, suggested by HPC

1. git clone as listed above. 
2. make release directory

New Commands:

3. module load gcc/5.2.0
4. module load boost/1.62-python2.7.10-gcc5.2.0
5. module display gcc 5.2.0 #Find executable path
6. module display boost/1.62-python2.7.10-gcc5.2.0 #Find boost Lib path 
7. export CC=/usr/local/Cluster-Apps/gcc/5.2.0/bin/gcc
8. export CXX=/usr/local/Cluster-Apps/gcc/5.2.0/bin/g++
9. Edit CMakeLists.txt and force it to use absolute paths by changing policy
Same as before: 

10. cmake -D CMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release ..
11. make -j 4   #for 4 threads of compilation (more if you can!)
12. ctest -j 4  #for 4 threads of testing
